               <interp inst="t18600507-495a" type="date" value="18600507"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18600507-495a-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-495a-18600507 t18600507-495a-offence-1 t18600507-495a-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>495. <persName id="def1-495a-18600507" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-495a-18600507" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-495a-18600507" type="age" value="25"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-495a-18600507" type="surname" value="VOWLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-495a-18600507" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">CHARLES VOWLES</hi> (25)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18600507-495a-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18600507-495a-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="breakingPeace"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18600507-495a-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="wounding"></interp>, Feloniously cutting and wounding <persName id="t18600507-name-716" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-716" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-716" type="surname" value="LUSCOMBE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-716" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18600507-495a-offence-1 t18600507-name-716"></join>James Luscombe</persName> with intent to murder him. <hi rend="italic">Second count.</hi> With intent to do him some grievous bodily harm.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS. METCALFE</hi> and <hi rend="smallCaps">BEASELEY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-717" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-717" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-717" type="surname" value="LUSCOMEE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-717" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES LUSCOMEE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, P.</hi>) On Wednesday night, 11th April, I was on duty in Pomeroy-street—the prisoner was given into my custody by a female who said in his presence that he had assaulted her—there were three marks of violence on her face—I told him he must go to the station with me—he said, "What! for two such b—y stinking wh—s as them; as for you, I will lay you dead in the road if you attempt to put a hand upon me"—I persuaded him to go to the station quietly, which he refused to do—I took hold of him by the arm—he was trying to get his arm away from me, and struck me a blow on the face—I took him by the cuff of his coat, and put my other hand inside his cravat and said, "Now then, for what you were going to do"—I took him to the station and he was dis<lb></lb>charged, the woman was obliged to take out a summons—I saw him again about five minutes after he left the station, near the Montpelier public-house, Queen's-road, Peckham—I was passing and he said, "Oh, you b—<hi rend="italic">smot</hi>; you have not got your wish to-night"—I told him it was not my wish to lock him up, and I had not said anything about it at the station; that I did not tell them he had assaulted me—he said, "No, you did not; will you come and have some beer?"—I said, "No, thank you"—I walked away—I saw him again about 12 o'clock at night, outside the Victoria beer-shop, in Pomeroy-street—I was still on my beat—he was halloing and making a great noise—I went down—several of his mates were there, and when he saw me he said, "This is the b—that took me to the station to-night, I should like to give him <hi rend="italic">a doing</hi>"—I persuaded him to go home, and think no more of it; two of his mates got hold of him—he said, "Let me go, I will give that b—<hi rend="italic">a doing</hi> to-night"—that was all he said that night—I saw him again the following night about 12 o'clock, in front of the Victoria public-house—Cox, a constable, was with me—I heard several people talking—the prisoner came out, I did not know he was there—he began halloing and said "I wonder where this b—<hi rend="italic">snot</hi> is who took me to the station last night, if I could see him I would soon do for him"—one of his mates pointed across the road and said, "There stand two"—the prisoner then ran across the road and said, "This is the b—that took me to the station last night," pointing to me—he came up quickly and said, "You are the one that took me to the station last night, are you not?"—I said, "Yes; have not you forgotten that yet?"—I persuaded him to think nothing more home—I said, "That is all settled as far as you and I are</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070211"></xptr>
               <p>concerned"—he said, "Yes, you b—, I will settle you yet"—I persuaded him to go home—he went a short distance up the street—I stopped there—he came back in about five minutes with one of his mates, and walked round me—his mate said, "Never mind, Charlie, we' are in our own street; we can do as we like here, and as for those b—<hi rend="italic">snots</hi>, it would take forty of them to take us to the station"—I said nothing—the prisoner came up to me and kept threatening me—I persuaded him to go away home—he shoved up against me at one time, and then went away up the street towards his own home—I did not follow him for nearly five minutes, and then that was the direction I was going in—I saw him standing at his own door, and passed him—he followed me almost directly—I was one or two paces in front of him—he kept on threatening me—I persuaded him to go in—he said, "Certainly, will you allow me to smoke my cigar?" putting it in his mouth—I said, "Certainly"—he said, "How can I smoke it without a light?"—I said, "You can get a light inside"—he said, "I think I have got a match here," putting his hand in his right pocket; and instead of taking out a match, he took out a knife, looked over his right shoulder as if he was going to strike a match, opened the knife, and I heard the spring of it—he threw his arm out to it's full length and aimed at my cheek or throat—I turned my head round over my shoulder, put it down, and received the stab just behind the left shoulder—he then rushed at me, and struck me with the knife in his hand—I had got my staff out and I struck at him and guarded the knife off—he rushed at me a third time in the same way, and I struck his hand and guarded the knife off—the fourth time I struck his hand and knocked the knife out of it, upon that he turned away from me as if he was going to run down the street—I saw my mate come up the street, and I called out, "Mind the knife, he has stabbed me"—he was run<lb></lb>ning as fast as he could—I saw him strike my mate and knock him down in the road—I followed—he ran down the street until he got to the passage from Pomeroy-street, and just as he was going through, I made a grasp at him, missed my aim, and fell over the posts—I got up, followed him, and caught him in Cameron-street—Cox was there—I sprang my rattle for assistance, and he was taken to the station—my shoulder had a very severe stab, and bled very much—I have not the use of it yet—I have been under medical care for some time—this knife (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>) was picked up—it is the one the prisoner had in his hand—I told the constable Holdaway where<lb></lb>abouts it was that I had been struck.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LILLEY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> At the time you saw him on the night of the 11th was not he partially in liquor when the two women came up? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Certainly he had been drinking—one of his mates was in his company—I do not know whether his name is Barraclough—I cannot say whether he followed to the station—I saw him outside the door when we came out—the prisoner was discharged at the station at a quarter to eleven—it was about twelve when I saw him in Pomeroy-street—I did not see him come out of the Victoria—I saw him outside, and I had not seen him go in—this was Tuesday in Easter week—I know England's manu<lb></lb>factory—I have heard since that the prisoner worked there—I do not know that the men were off work at that time on account of the holidays—there were several other men, who I call his mates, outside the Victoria—he crossed the road to me—I am quite sure a woman spoke to me while I was there, I did not know her, I have not seen her since—she did not advise me not to interfere with the man, and not to take any notice of him, for he was very drunk—no woman spoke to me to that effect—there is not the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070212"></xptr>
               <p>least forgetfulness on my part—the prisoner was not led away by any of his mates, not on the 12th, the second night—he was not so much in liquor that he required assistance in going home—he had been drinking, but he knew well what he was about—he made four attacks on me and ran away—I had not taken him into custody that night before this—I was attacked in Pomeroy-street, about 150 yards from the Victoria, near the place where the prisoner lodges with a person named Gray—I knocked the knife out of his hand and ran after him, saying, "Mind the knife, he has stabbed me"—I ran 300 or 400 yards after him before I caught him—I fell with violence on the same shoulder on which I had received the injury—I ultimately took him into custody myself—I had never seen him before the night of the 11th—there was a man named Crutcher there—I cannot; say whether he had been drinking at the Victoria—he seemed to have been drinking, but he knew very well what he was about—the expression I referred to, about forty policemen taking him to the station, was used by the other man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was your shoulder cut before you fell? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; there were not any stones where I fell; but whether there were or not my shoulder was cut by the knife—the woman spoke to me after the prisoner had gone away the first time; I can't say whether she came to caution me—she did not say, "For God's sake, policeman, go away; whatever you do, don't interfere with them"—the prisoner came back to me while the woman was speaking to me.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-718" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-718" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-718" type="surname" value="COX"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-718" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES COX</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, P</hi> 346.) On 12th April, about twelve o'clock, I was in Clifton-fields—I met Luscombe in Pomeroy-street—I remember the people turning out from the Victoria public-house, and among others the prisoner—we were then standing on the other side of the street—the prisoner crossed over, pointed to Luscombe, and said, "That is the b—that took me to the station; it would take forty b—policemen to take me there to-night; if ever you put a hand upon me again it will be worse for you," or "I will do for you"—Luscombe told him that he had nothing to say to him, and said, u Why don't you go away home?"—a man then came out of the public-house with some beer; he asked for a drink—he said, "Why don't you drink and go home?"—the prisoner said, u The police<lb></lb>man did more than his duty last night;" and he said that he would keep in the street all night if he liked—I then went on my beat, and left Lus<lb></lb>combe to go on his—a few minutes afterwards Crutcher called me—I went up the street, and found the prisoner in Luscombe's custody—Luscombe was staggering back, and said to me, "Look out for the knife"—I made a catch at the prisoner to catch hold of him very quickly, and I received a blow from him on the side of my head with something very hard; I believe it was not his fist—I did not see anything in his hand, but I think there must have been something beyond that which nature gave him—a stone in a handkerchief would produce such an effect as I felt; I was knocked down Benseless—two or three minutes after I came to myself I found that Lus-combe had taken the prisoner—I followed them to the station, and found Luscombe bleeding from the back—I saw the prisoner at the station, and found on him this stone (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>)—it was done up in this handkerchief in the way it is now; there was a knot tied above the stone to keep it there—the prisoner was charged with stabbing Luscombe—he said, "You have not found the knife"—that was all he said—he had been drinking, but was not drunk; he knew what he was about.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How far is it from Pomeroy-street to the station; about a mile? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, not half a mile: it is about that—I have been</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070213"></xptr>
               <p>stationed there about eighteen months—I saw by the prisoner's manner that he had been drinking—I had not seen him that or the preceding day—I have known him by sight; I believe he works at England's factory—I searched him and found this stone in his pocket—I found Lusoombe stag<lb></lb>gering when I ran up—I did not see any one in the street but Luscombe and the prisoner—I saw no one after I left the public-house—I did not see Luscombe have anything outside the pnblio-house—I believe a pint of beer was brought out; I did not see Crutcher and Luscombe partake of it—I saw the prisoner take hold of it, but do not know whether he drank; I walked away; I took none of it—I do not know what Luscombe took—I lost my senses—I am quite sure of that—Crutcher took me up—I believe they ran into Kendall-street—I did not follow them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-719" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-719" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-719" type="surname" value="HOLDAWAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-719" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HOLDAWAY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Policeman, P</hi> 219). On Thursday night; in conse<lb></lb>quence of what Luscombe told me, I went into Pomeroy-street, and found this knife lying in the carriage-road, about two yards from the footway, near the spot where Luscombe described that he had been assaulted—it was open as it is now, and slightly wet with a little rain that had fallen—I took it to the station and gave it to the sergeant.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Do you know the Victoria? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, it is about half way between the Victoria and the Queen's-road, about two hundred yards from the Victoria—I found it about 4 in the morning—I am sure that was about the time—while I was searching only one of the constables spoke to me, the one who was on the beat in Luscombe's place—no civilian spoke to me—I looked about the entrance to Kendall-street and Powis-place, which leads from Pomeroy-street to Kendall-street.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you find it near the place pointed out to you by Luscombe? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Luscombe described that place.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-720" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-720" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-720" type="surname" value="COOMBES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-720" type="given" value="ELIZABETH MATILDA"></interp>ELIZABETH MATILDA COOMBES</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 45, Bedford-cottages, Peckham—on 11th April, in consequence of something which had been done to me, I gave the prisoner into custody, and went to the station—I had sent for a policeman—as I followed to the station, I heard the prisoner say to Luscombe, "I will do for you, I will watch you"—he used bad language, but I could not say what words—I never saw him to my knowledge before that night.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> I believe you drank with him on that night? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> By his pushing me into the place—he went quietly to the station after the police<lb></lb>man had hold of him—he was discharged there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-721" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-721" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-721" type="surname" value="CRUTCHER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-721" type="given" value="JOSIAH"></interp>JOSIAH CRUTCHER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a dairyman in Pomeroy-street—on the night of 12th April, about a quarter to 12, I was at the Victoria public-house, and saw the prisoner—he was not drunk, but he had been drinking—he went out before me and was talking to the two constables—he was threatening Luscombe that he would do for him, for some grievance that had happened the night before—he said, "This is the b that took me last night, he shall never take me any more"—I got a pot of beer for my supper in a can and asked the prisoner to drink, saying, "Do not say any more, go home"—he drank, I believe, and Luscombe said, "I do not want to have anything to say to you, as far as last night, that is forgotten, and if you do not say anything to me I shall say nothing to you"—he walked on and I stopped behind—Luscombe followed him—I then followed and saw them some dis<lb></lb>tance off struggling together—I stepped back and spoke to Cox—I after<lb></lb>wards saw Cox knocked down—I assisted him up and stopped with him—the prisoner ran away; Cox was insensible for five minutes.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How long had you been at the Victoria? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About ten minutes—I had not been there before—I had left Deptford at 11 o'clock</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070214"></xptr>
               <p>—I do not say I had not had a glass of beer anywhere—I came home with an old gentleman; there were three of us, we had a pint or a pot, I don't know which—I was as sober as I am at this moment; I had half a glass of gin at the Victoria—if I had had two or three pints of beer it would not have made much difference to me—I heard the prisoner say, "No forty policemen shall take me to the station"—he was a little <hi rend="italic">fresh</hi>—I did not know him till the day before, as I stood at my gate he walked up with two or three friends.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-722" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-722" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-722" type="surname" value="FLOWER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-722" type="given" value="JOHN SWAN"></interp>JOHN SWAN FLOWER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a surgeon, of Camberwell-green—I attended Luscombe, I found him in bed—he had a clean-cut wound about an inch or rather larger, penetrating to the bone—it had been given with considerable force, and much against the bone, and if it had not met with an interposition of that kind it would have been very serious—he was otherwise bruised on the shoulder, such a bruise might arise from a fall, but the other was a clean cut, and must in my judgment have been caused by some such instrument as this—he has been under my care ever since, and is still unable to use his arm.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> How are you able to know that the bone was pene<lb></lb>trated? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> It did not heal kindly, and an effusion of blood followed—I do not think falling on the shoulder immediately after or at the time would aggravate the appearances—if a man received a cut and fell on it the surrounding muscles might be affected—I do not think a flat stone would have done it—the macadamized roads with stones with projecting points could not do it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you see the clothes? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, they were cat right through clean.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LILLEY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">J. CRUTCHER</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you see a person named Lowes after you had been before the police Magistrate? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I never heard the name, and do not know any such person—I never spoke to a person on 25th April and said, "Good morning, Sir, you had your journey for nothing the other morning"—I do not know what you are alluding to.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LILLEY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">WILLIAM LOW</hi>. I am a blacksmith, and live at Pomeroy-street, Hatcham—I work in the same factory as the prisoner—he has worked there sinoe June last—he has borne the character of a quiet, inoffensive man—he lives in the same street, and I never saw him drink so much as half a pint of beer—I never knew him quarrel with a man—on 12th April, about twelve at night, I was going to the Victoria Arms, and saw him standing outside the door—he was very tipsy, I have not the slightest doubt about that—I said, "<hi rend="italic">Charley</hi>, why do not you go home?"—he said, "Well, I am going," and made a bit of a move—the tallest policeman came across the road to him and said, "Are you going home?"—<hi rend="italic">Charley</hi> said, "You mind your own business, you go and do your duty"—and he laid hold of him by the jacket and said, "It is my business to clear the street of such vagabonds as you"—he left go of him and he regained his feet across the road—the policeman took him by the neck and jerked him in that position from the Victoria down to Powis-court, where the prisoner got away from him—a man named Croucher, a cow-keeper, was there, but he was very tipsy, he could scarcely stand—I went to the Victoria for some beer for supper—I had not had as much as half a pint—I had been working overtime—when the prisoner got away from the policeman, the policeman drew his staff from one of his pockets, and Cox, the shorter policeman, hit him on the jaw and knocked him down—he ran to the other side, and the tall policeman hit him with his</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070215"></xptr>
               <p>staff across the middle of the arm, and then he ran across the road again and through Powis-court—I said to Cox, "Why do not you leave this man alone? he is a very quiet man, if you leave him for a few minutes he will go home"—he said, "Yes, I will, but my mate won't"—I saw no knife, if there had been one in the prisoner's hand at that time I must have seen it; I was close to him—I never saw him use a knife like this (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>), and I have known him some months—I never knew him to have anything more than a small pen-knife, which he used to take pieces of dirt out of men's eyes with, and he used to borrow my knife sometimes—I used a rasp, and pieces of scale very often fly from the iron into the eyes—when I arrived at the Victoria Arms it was shut—(I saw Crutcher the same week that the hearing was at the Court)—the policeman was picked up by Crutcher, and he picked his hat up for him and wanted to know which way he had gone, which he actually did not know—I took the policemen down the street and walked with them—I saw no sparring between Luscombe and the prisoner with his staff—I saw him strike at him in the middle of the road—I could not hear any policeman say, "Look out for the knife, or mind the knife,"because I was behind the two policemen when Cox received the blow—I heard Luscombe make no complaint while I was there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You worked with the prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I worked for the same firm—I was not out with him during the Easter holidays—I was at work—I went to the Victoria that night about five minutes past 12, for the first time—I had come from Greenwich, from my wife's mother's—I wfent to fetch my wife home—I went to the Victoria for my supper beer—I had a brother there, and I ran to get some beer—he is at home—I generally go to the Victoria for my supper beer, and they were just coming out—the house was closed, but I knocked at the door—the landlord opened it and I got the beer—the policeman was standing on the other side of the road—Luscombe came right across to the prisoner, and a number of men who had just come out of the Victoria—the milkman was standing on the other side of the way—I did not see the prisoner remain there after his mates had left—he was there—he remained by himself—there was nobody but I and the fmillrmjui—Luscombe came over and said, "Are not you going homef"—he said, "Go and mind your own business; go and do your duty," and Luscombe collared him by the neck, shoved him across the road, and said, "It is my duty to clear the streets of such vagabonds as you"—nothing was said about his having been previously at the station that night—he pushed him up the street, and Cox followed, and the milk<lb></lb>man and I, until they came to Powis-court—I know where the prisoner lives—they went opposite his house, and pushed him past it—the prisoner got away when Luscombe was shaking him, and he put his hand behind to get his trunchepn—Cox ran in between, and the prisoner hit him with his left hand on the jaw—Cox lay on the ground about two minutes—Crutcher picked him up, and then he ran into Powis-court—that was immediately after Cox was knocked down—I swear there was no knife—it was just under a gas lamp, and if there had been a knife I must have seen it—I never heard a word about a knife—I do not know whether the policeman stabbed him<lb></lb>self, but I never saw anybody by whom such a cut could have been inflicted on him—I never heard of it till next morning, and I am quite sure he was not stabbed that night; if he was it was when he was in the other street—I did not see him stagger while he was in my presence—I did not follow them to Powis-court or to the station—I went a week afterwards to the police-court—I did not know that the charge was not true, because he might</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070216"></xptr>
               <p>have done it in the other street—no one gave evidence in his favour that I know of—I have not visited the prisoner—I know him by working with him hut if a man comes in drunk we know that he is a drunken man—he works up to nearly 8 o'clock, and sometimes till 10—I am a blacksmith and boiler-maker—he does not work in the same shop—I never saw him drunk—if I go for a walk I might meet him by chance, just as I might meet you—I have no other means than that of knowing whether he is a sober man—I never saw him quarrel in my life—I never heard anything of his knocking down the woman on the previous night—I heard it at the police-court—I heard her say that he struck her, but never heard her say that she was covered with blood.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LILLEY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you ever see him drunk before that night? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Never; I have had opportunities of seeing him before, of an evening—there were twenty or thirty men on the drink on this Easter holiday—they were not at work that week—I was at the police-court, but was not called—I went to know whether there was any truth in the case—I understood that the stabbing had been in the other street.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-723" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-723" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-723" type="surname" value="BARRACLOUGH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-723" type="given" value="SAMUEL"></interp>SAMUEL BARRACLOUGH</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a boiler-maker, of Pomeroy-street, Hatcham—I work at the factory—I was with the prisoner on 11th April, in the evening, at a public-house in the Bath-road, and saw there the witness who has been examined here to-day, and another woman, Coombs—they were in the side bar of the public-house—the prisoner and I were drinking in the front bar—they beckoned to us to go to them—we did so, and they asked us for a drop of gin—the prisoner paid for half a pint of gin and peppermint, and a couple of biscuits—the prosecutrix and the female had some words, and went out—the prisoner followed her, and caught hold of her arm—she wrenched hold of his hand, said he had hurt her, and struck him—he took no notice, but took it in good part, and struck her again—she struck him on the face, in the jaw—she came inside, and he came after her—she struck at him again—he said, "Drop that"—she struck him again, and he said, "If you don't be quiet, I shall smack your face"—she struck him again, and he smacked her face—she was not covered with blood—shehad a slight scratch on her cheek, but I perceived no blood—we came out to go home, to get ready for work in the morning—they were outside, and said that they would give the prisoner in charge to the first policeman they came to—we went down Pomeroy-street, and met a policeman—she said, "I give that man in charge to you"—he said "What for?" she said, "For smacking my face" he took his lamp, looked at her face, and there was a scratch on it—the prisoner said, "She struck me several times, didn't she, <hi rend="italic">Sam?</hi>" I said, "Yes"—he had his light there, and Baid, "Where did he strike you?" she said, "Here"—he could see no mark, but collared the prisoner by his handkerchief, and said, "You come with me," holding him with one hand, and the light with the other—the prisoner said, "Let me go; if you want me to go with you, I will go quietly"—the policeman let him go, and we all went away together to the station—I wanted to go in, but they would not allow me, and policeman 161 and the other went in together—I did not hear the prisoner utter any threat at that time, or strike Luscombe any blow—I was near enough to have seen him do so—I continued near them until they reached the station at Peckham—I am positively sure no blow was struck by the prisoner—I have known him since February—he has been quite mild since I have known him—he has not been accustomed to fight with people.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Do you not call knocking down a woman anything?</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070217"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He did not knock her down, he simply slapped her face with his open hand—the mark on her face was not a bump, it was a scratch; his finger<lb></lb>nail must have cut her face—I perceived no blood on her shawl; I can only speak to what I saw—he did not knock her down' m the public-house; he hit her with his open hand—he did not hit her with his fist on the jaw, and knock her down—I will swear she was not knocked down by him in my presence, and I was there all the time—I did not see her fall down—the other woman was sitting in a chair when this business was going on—the prisoner and I did not force her into the public-house, force her down into a chair, and keep her there—they did not try to leave the public-house—I did not hear him, when the policeman took him, Bay anything about two aach b—stinking w—s, nor "If you lay hands on me I will lay you dead in the road;" nothing of the kind—I followed them all the way to the station—he did not say, going to the station, "I will do for you; I will watch you"—I work with the prisoner—I have never drank with hint before that night, unless it might be a night when we were having a pint of ale after supper, and then gone home—I have never been in his company above twice before in a public-house—the landlord was not present at the Bath tavern when this little bit of a woman was beating this man—the mistress was there—I do not know whether she is here—I never saw the barman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LILLEY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you see this man knock down Coombs or the other woman? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, and I was there all the time, so that I most have seen it—when the charge was made by the woman to the policeman, the prisoner mid, "She struck me several times over on the face"—the prisoner came away with me from the station.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-724" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-724" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-724" type="surname" value="CURTAIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-724" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>SARAH CURTAIN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of John Curtain, of Pomcroy-street, Hatcham—on the night of 12th April I was standing at my doof at half-past 11 o'clock, waiting for my husband—a policeman spoke to me as he passed; I have not seen him here to-day that I know of—I saw another policeman; a short one—they crossed over to the Victoria tavern, which is right opposite, and the short policeman stayed a little time, till the tail policeman came and went into the Victoria, and brought out a pint pot—those are the two policemen, (<hi rend="italic">Luscombe and Cox</hi>)—they partook of it; the tall one then took it back—Orutcher, the milkman, came up, and a joke passed between them—Crutcher was very tipsy—Mr. Greedy was turning them all out of his house, as it was 12 o'clock, and the prisoner came out and crossed to the kerb—I knew him before going backwards and forwards—they were on the edge of the pavement, against the sign-poet, drinking the beer, and Crutcher in front of them—I did not observe how the prisoner came out; it was very dark; they had <hi rend="italic">douted</hi> the lamps—I went in half an hour before to ask for my husband, and the prisoner was very tipsy in front of the bar, bat I did not notice what state he came out in, whether steadily or not—my husband came oat after the prisoner, and persuaded him to go quietly up the street—I remained at my door the whole time till Vowles went away—my husband pursued him, but he said he would not go home, because he knew his mates were not gone home—when the policeman went away my husband took him up the street, and laid hold of his arm—Vowles needed support; he was very tipsy—when he was gone the policeman knocked at the public-house door—Mr. Greedy said, "Who is there?" and while they were talking, the prisoner came down again, and knocked at the door—the policeman said, "You go away home," in a very gruff manner—the prisoner said, "You go away, and go on your duty"—the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070218"></xptr>
               <p>policeman said, "You had better be off home," and be pusbed him in <hi rend="italic">jerks</hi>, and collared him by the back of the coat—he got him past where he lodged, and we did not go any further—I crossed the road, and saw him go away—he is a very rough, powerful man, but a very sober man—it is very seldom he gets drunk—the policeman said, u Do not be mistaken; we took him last night; he is the biggest coward out; I gave him two or three good shakings last night; he is the d—dest coward out"—he went up the street with my husband, and we heard a running away—the prisoner was very tipsy; he could scarcely stand—I did not see the policeman take his staff out; neither of them had their staves out in my presence.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you hear the prisoner say anything to the policeman? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did not—the policeman said something about going to the station last night, but the prisoner did not—the prisoner went across the road to the other side—the policemen were not there then—my husband was trying to get him home—he did not cross the road directly after he got out of the public-house—his mates live on the other side, and he said he would go and see if they had come home—I have seen one of his mates here, Barraclough.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You saw him on this night? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—he was very drunk, and he went home before Vowles came out—the prisoner went and knocked at his door—the policeman was then on the Victoria side of the road—my husband went with the prisoner—I saw the prisoner talking to the policeman, but do not know what was said—there were no loud words at all, or noise, or hallooing, or disturbance—I am quite sure I saw no staff taken out—I saw the policeman with his staff out afterwards—we were still at the door when we heard the running, we had never gone in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is your husband here? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; nor is the landlord or landlady of the public-house that I am aware of—the policeman fell in Powis-place—he jumped up and ran again directly; and the prisoner stopped and the policeman stopped—the policeman stood on the pavement and the prisoner in the road—I said, "Oh! policeman, do let the poor man go home"—he went like this, and I said, "Oh, policeman, hit a woman!"—he said, "I will hit anybody that interrupts me"</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where was Mr. Low? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not know—he persuaded the prisoner to go home—I heard the prisoner's voice after the prosecutor said that—he cried for mercy, and he called for my husband; I knew his voice—Mr. Low was not there at the time my husband persuaded the prisoner to go away; he came after that, when the prisoner came back, but I did not know him—he was there when the prisoner said, "You go away home, and do your duty"—he went with the prisoner past my house, and I did not see what became of him after that—I did not see the prisoner fall—I saw Luscombe fall—I did not see Cox, the short policeman, at that time—I went up to where the policeman fell—I did not see Cox lying on the ground—my husband is at work; he has not beeu here—he did not know that he would be required—I did not go before the Magistrate—my husband was not very tipsy, but he had had enough beer.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-725" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-725" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-725" type="surname" value="FOX"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-725" type="given" value="ANN"></interp>ANN FOX</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of James Fox, of Pomeroy-street—on Friday night, 12th April, a few minutes before 12 o'clock, I sent my daughter Ellen into the Victoria, while I waited outside—I saw the two prisoners standing by the sign-post and one of them had a pot in his hand—I did not see the prisoner or hear his voice; all I heard was talking inside the Victoria.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-726" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-726" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-726" type="surname" value="FOX"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-726" type="given" value="ELLEN"></interp>ELLEN FOX</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a daughter of the last witness—I went into the Victoria on 12th April, at a few minutes to 12 o'clock, while she waited outside—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186005070219"></xptr>
               <p>saw the prisoner then very much the worse for liquor—there were two persons standing outside, one had a pewter pot in his hand—they were still there when I came out, I saw no one with them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18600507-name-727" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-727" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-727" type="surname" value="GRAY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18600507-name-727" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH GRAY</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Pomeroy-street, Hatcham—the prisoner has lodged with me since a week before last Christmas—I knew nothing of him before further than seeing him pass to go to work—his character has been very good—he has been a sober industrious young man—I never saw this knife in his possession.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">ELIZABETH COMIS</hi>. On 11th April I had been in the Bath tavern with a young woman, a friend of mine, having gin and peppermint—the prisoner was at the private bar, but I did not see him at first—he had this young man with him (<hi rend="italic">Barracfough</hi>)—as I was coming out the prisoner was at the door with a glass of ale in his hand, and asked us to drink it; we refused—his friend caught hold of my friend and the prisoner caught hold of me by the arm, and pushed me back in at the private entrance, and asked us both what we would have to drink; we said that we had had quite enough—my friend said, "If we have anything we will have some gin and peppermint"—we had some and called for two biscuits—and then the young men went behind the door with my friend, talking to her—I was standing by myself, and wont out to see the time, I found it was twenty-five minutes to 10—I said, "Come, Sarah, it is time we got home, your mother will wonder where we are"—she came running out and the prisoner got hold of her in a shocking manner—I said, "You, leave her alone, and let her come on"—he instantly caught hold of me behind and got my head partly doubled to my feet—I said, "You good for nothing creature, you had better let me alone"—he said, "Come tick and have some drink"—I tried to get away, but could not, and he struck me on" the jaw and dug his nail into my hand; here is the mark now—he went away in at the private entrance, and I went in and stamped my foot and said that he should not strike me like that—I struck at him and he struck me two blows, one was over the eye, and I instantly fell senseless—the people ran round and got me in the parlour, ordered the company to go out, and begged me not to let the prisoner go away—the policeman brought Borne water, and my friend washed my face—I sent my friend out to see if there was a policeman—she never returned, and I found the two men walking away—I called, "Police," but no assistance came—I afterwards gave the prisoner in charge—the blows were struck violently with his full force; here is blocd on my shawl now, but it has dried in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. LILLEY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is Sarah here? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I did not beckon to the men, or speak to them at all—nor did Sarah in iny presence—we drank with them—I do not get my living in any other way besides that which I have mentioned—I was coming home from my work in the Bath-road—I struck at the prisoner once, I cannot say whether I struck him—he did not show the policeman the mark on his face, he said, "She struck me on the face"—there was no mark to be seen—I mean to say that the blood on this shawl came from my face—my nose bled where the cut was, and over my eye-I mean to say that the blood trickled down from my nose—I have not washed it since—I had not passed half a dozen words with the prisoner, and I gave him no cause—I went with him to the station, and heard that I might take out a summons—I went to take one out, but did nob, because there was a misunderstanding; Mr. Mprton did not under<lb></lb>stand my woids.</p>
